column1: 70105;instagram;2019-01-19 09:20:33;FALSE;"to all people out there struggling with #ptsd :
it's been four month now since i absolved my last therapy. it was the first time i learned about ptbs and the symptomes. it's not like i didn't feel them earlier
column2: but in the therapy i had the chance to learn that i am not suffering alone. ptbs is a serious disorder and there are so many people out there suffering without anyone to talk to about their feelings. about worst nightmares
column3: highest amount of fear and fighting against it. there also will be people
column4: that will call you a psychopath. people who don't or don't want to understand what you have been through and that you survived biggest pain - most people luckily couldn't even imagine. you are way more then a diagnose and you are worth to love and forgive yourself! never ever (!!) let anyone tell you
column5: you wouldn't be worth it and that you are hopeless
column6: manipulative or anything else. please get rid of those toxic people in your life. they will destroy you
column7: even if they are the people you love the most. you are not alone! every time i met someone with ptbs or trauma experience
column8: i felt the unconditionally solidarity between us. never stop talking about what happend. never give up yourself and the most important thing: never let toxic people tell you
column9: you wouldn't be worth anything. you are more then that. never give up growing. i love you.

column1: 70477;instagram;2019-01-19 00:19:28;FALSE;"you see this ""to do"" list...it may not look like much but for me this was a huge accomplishment!  since the attack my short term memory as well as my energy level has been shot!  i can't always remember what it is i need to do or am wanting to do and when i can remember i don't always have the energy to complete the task...not to mention if there are multiple tasks i can become easily overwhelmed...all symptoms of truama related ptsd!
but yestersay... yesterday i not only remembered my tasks for the day
column2: i completed them with help from my husband lol.  i even managed to go out into the world and people then came home and completed my tasks!  it's a big win for me no matter how small and i'll take it!

column1: 70510;instagram;2019-01-18 23:33:18;FALSE;"letâ€™s get real with whyt again. warning
if you were to look at my instagram profile earlier last year
column2: it would have looked like i was in a happy
column4: relationship with a boyfriend. little did you know
column5: that i was being sexually and mentally abused while also suffering with extreme anxiety and depression. earlier this year
column6: i shared my #nofilter story via video telling my mental illness story. now i am choosing to take off yet another filter of my story. i was raped
column8: and abused. as i am healing from this trauma
column9: i have become passionate about being an advocate for abuse and mental illness. i want to make clear my intentions of sharing this. i am not sharing out of spite
column11: or attention. the details of who and what are not important. iâ€™m more concerned about speaking up for those victims like myself. i am doing this for the girl that i once was who was so lost
column13: and living such dark things. i am choosing to take back my power and use it to empower. i cannot stay silent. i will make my voice heard. the world is ignorant regarding abusive relationships and victims of rape and sexual assault but iâ€™m here to change that

column1: check the link in my bio to watch my part two #nofilter video about my experiences regarding my abuse. #metoo
and stay tuned for my podcast launch where i will continue sharing my journey and insights.

column1: 70634;instagram;2019-01-18 22:03:07;FALSE;"it is a sad state of affairs that women walking alone at night must worry for their safety. not only at night but even during the day. .

if iâ€™m walking somewhere and there are no other people around my senses go on â€œalertâ€. i put my mindfulness into my peripheral vision. i toss my hair to give me a chance to nonchalantly look over my shoulder without seeming to do so
column2: and check thereâ€™s no danger lurking. iâ€™ll put my keys between my fingers to get ready to use them as a weapon. iâ€™ll get out my phone and call someone to ensure iâ€™m connected to another person or get ready with the keypad to dial 000 quickly if i need to. and itâ€™s probably 2-3 times per week iâ€™m in a potential situation like this (without even taking any real risks! just as part of every day life.) luckily iâ€™ve never had to truly defend myself like this. but as we have seen in the case of aiia maasarwe in melbourne this week

column2: i know itâ€™s been a while. i have a story for you but i also just wanted to remind you all that if you ever have any stories to share feel free to message me

i was on an afternoon walk in town. a car pulled over and rolled its window down. i stopped and looked into the car (maybe they were asking for directions?) only to find a man grinning and eyeing me up and down. yâ€™all know that feeling? the gross one that makes you feel like nothing more than an object? yeah

column1: the man was saying things to me
column2: but i started walking away as fast as possible. he followed behind me
column3: slowly rolling along the curb side while i fumbled around with my phone. i called my dadâ€”just so that i could be on the phone with someone. when my dad picked up i immediately started bawling. after being on the phone
column4: the car disappeared and i walked as fast as possible back home
